'''''Fort Stikine''''' was a British [[Fort ship]] which was built in Canada in 1942. Owned by the American [[War Shipping Administration]], she was leased under [[bareboat charter|charter]] to the [[Ministry of War Transport]] under the [[Lend-Lease]] scheme and operated under the management of the [[Port Line]]. ''Fort Stikinne'' only had a short career, and was destroyed in [[Bombay Explosion (1944)|an explosion]] at [[Bombay]], [[British Raj|India]], in April 1944 that caused the loss of a further thirteen ships.

==Construction==
''Fort Stikine'' was {{convert|441|ft|5|in|m|2}} long, with a beam of {{convert|57|ft|2|in|m|2}}. She had a depth of {{convert|35|ft|0|in|m|2}} and a draught of {{convert|26|ft|11.5|in|m|2}}. The ship was propelled by a 505 [[nominal horsepower|NHP]] [[triple expansion steam engine]] which was built by the Dominion Engineering Works, [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada. It had cylinders of 24{{frac|1|2}} inches (62&nbsp;cm)<!--{{convert|24.5|in|cm}}-->, {{convert|37|in|cm}} and {{convert|70|in|cm}} bore by {{convert|48|in|cm}} stroke.<ref name=Stikine43>{{cite web |url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=43b0370.pdf |title=LLOYD'S REGISTER, NAVIRES A VAPEUR ET A MOTEURS |publisher=Plimsoll Ship Data |accessdate=13 August 2013}}</ref>

==History==
''Fort Stikine'' was built by Prince Rupert Drydock & Shipyard, [[Prince Rupert, British Columbia]], Canada as yard number 43. She was launched on 31 July 1942.<ref name=SBH>{{cite web |url=http://shipbuildinghistory.com/history/canada/princerupert.htm|title=Prince Rupert Dry Dock, Prince Rupert BC |publisher=Shipbuilding History |accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref> The ship was owned by the American [[War Shipping Administration]] and [[bareboat charter|chartered]] to the British [[Ministry of War Transport]], who placed her under the management of the [[Port Line]]. The United Kingdom Official Number 168351 and [[Code Letters]] BKLG were allocated. Her port of registry was [[London]].<ref name=Stikine43/>

[[File:Ussborie dd215 dht.jpg|thumb|The {{sclass|Clemson|destroyer}} {{USS|Borie|DD-215|6}} was one of the six warships that escorted Convoy ZG&nbsp;8.]]
''Fort Stikine'' departed from [[New Westminster]], [[British Columbia]], Canada on 7 September 1942 and arrived at [[Vancouver]] the next day. She then sailed to [[Comox, British Columbia]], arriving on 10 September. She sailed two days later for [[Victoria, British Columbia]] arriving on 13 September. ''Fort Stikine'' sailed that day for [[Los Angeles, California]], United States, where she arrived on 23 September. She sailed five days later for [[Balboa, Panama]], arriving on 10 October. After transiting the [[Panama Canal]], ''Fort Stikine'' departed from [[Crist<U+00F3>bal, Col<U+00F3>n|Cristobal]], Panama on 17 October with Convoy&nbsp;ZG8.<ref name=Port>{{cite web |url=http://convoyweb.org.uk/ports/index.html?search.php?vessel=FORT%20STIKINE~armain |title=FORT STIKINE |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> The convoy consisted eighteen merchant vessels escorted by six [[United States Navy]] warships. It arrived at [[Guantanamo Bay]], Cuba on 21 October.<ref name=ZG8>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/zg/index.html?zg.php?convoy=8!~zgmain |title=Convoy ZG.8 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref>

[[File:HMS Borage FL2711.jpg|thumb|The {{sclass|Flower|corvette}} {{HMS|Borage|K120|6}} was one of the seventeen escorts of Convoy HX&nbsp;214.]]
''Fort Stikine'' departed from Guantanamo Bay on 23 October as a member of Convoy GN&nbsp;14. The unescorted convoy consisted of 33 merchant ships; it arrived at [[New York City|New York]] on 30 October.<ref name=GN14>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/gn/index.html?gn.php?convoy=14!~gnmain |title=Convoy GN.14 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> She departed on 3 November with Convoy HX&nbsp;214. The convoy consisted of 33 merchant ships, escorted by a total of seventeen warships over the duration of the convoy. ''Fort Stikine'' carried general cargo and mails. The convoy arrived at [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]], United Kingdom on 14 December.<ref name=HX214>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/hx/index.html?hx.php?convoy=214!~hxmain |title=Convoy HX.214 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> She then sailed to the [[River Clyde|Clyde]], arriving on 16 December.<ref name=Port/>

[[File:The Royal Navy during the Second World War A12715.jpg|thumb|[[anti-aircraft artillery|Flak ship]] {{HMS|Pozarica}} was one of the 30 escorts of Convoy MKS&nbsp;6.]]
''Fort Stikine'' departed from the Clyde on 24 December with Convoy KMS&nbsp;6G. The convoy comprised 60 merchant ships escorted by a total of 22 warships over the duration of the convoy. The [[CAM ship]] {{SS|Empire Darwin||2}} also provided some protection to the convoy. Two merchant ships were lost to enemy action and another was damaged. The convoy arrived at [[B<U+00F4>ne]], [[French Algeria|Algeria]] on 8 January 1943,<ref name=KMS6G>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/kms/index.html?kms.php?convoy=6G!~kmsmain |title=Convoy KMS.6G |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> but ''Fort Stikine'' had split from the convoy the previous day and arrived at [[Oran]], Algeria. She sailed on 21 January to join Convoy MKS&nbsp;6,<ref name=Port/> which had departed from [[Philippeville, Algeria]] on 19 January and arrived back at Liverpool on 1 February. The convoy consisted of 50 merchant ships escorted by a total of 30 warships over the duration of the convoy, which also included ''Empire Darwin''. One merchant vessel was lost to enemy action. The convoy arrived at Liverpool on 1 February.<ref name=MKS6>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/mks/index.html?mks.php?convoy=6!~mksmain |title=Convoy MKS.6 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> ''Fort Stikine'' had left the convoy off [[Ireland]] and arrived at the Clyde on 31 January.<ref name=Port/>

[[File:U 87 Kriegsmarine.jpg|thumb|[[German Type VII submarine|Type VII submarine]] {{GS|U-87|1941|2}} attacked Convoy KMS&nbsp;10G, but was sunk by {{HMCS|Shediac|K110|6}} and {{HMCS|St. Croix|I81|6}}.]][[File:ORP Blyskawica na Atlantyku.jpg|thumb|{{sclass|Grom|destroyer}} {{ship|ORP|B<U+0142>yskawica}} was one of the nine warships that escorted Convoy SL&nbsp;129.]]
''Fort Stikine'' was a member of Convoy KMS&nbsp;10G, which departed from the Clyde on 26 February. It consisted of 62 merchant ships, escorted by a total of nineteen warships over the duration of the convoy. One merchant ship was sunk and three were damaged by enemy action. On 4 March {{GS|U-87|1941|2}} attacked the convoy, but was attacked with [[depth charge]]s and sunk by {{HMCS|Shediac|K110|6}} and {{HMCS|St. Croix|I81|6}}. The convoy arrived at B<U+00F4>ne on 11 March.<ref name=KMS10G>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/kms/index.html?kms.php?convoy=10G!~kmsmain |title=Convoy KMS.10G |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> As with Convoy KMS&nbsp;6G, ''Fort Stikine'' left the convoy and arrived at Oran a day earlier. She sailed on 31 March to join Convoy ET&nbsp;16,<ref name=Port/> which had departed from B<U+00F4>ne earlier that day. The unescorted convoy included fifteen merchant vessels, two of which were sunk by enemy action. ET&nbsp;16 arrived at [[Gibraltar]] on 1 April.<ref name=ET16>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/misc/index.html?yy.php?convoy=ET.16!~miscmain |title=Convoy ET.16 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> The ''Fort Stikine'' then joined Convoy RS&nbsp;4, which departed on 14 April. The unescorted convoy, comprising nineteen merchant ships, arrived at [[Freetown]], Sierra Leone on 25 April.<ref name=RS4>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/misc/index.html?yy.php?convoy=RS.4!~miscmain |title=Convoy RS.4 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> Laden with a cargo of [[iron ore]], ''Fort Stikine'' departed with Convoy SL&nbsp;129 on 11 May. The convoy, comprising 47 merchant ships and nine warships, combined at sea with Convoy MKS&nbsp;13 on 24 May.<ref name=SL129>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/sl2/index.html?sl.php?convoy=129!~slmain |title=Convoy SL.129 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> The combined convoy arrived at Liverpool on 1 June.<ref name=SK129MK>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/sl2/index.html?sl.php?convoy=129MK!~slmain |title=Convoy SL.129/MKS.13 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> ''Fort Stikine'' left the convoy before arrival at Liverpool and entered [[Loch Ewe]]. She then sailed to [[Middlesbrough]], [[North Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]], via convoys WN&nbsp;436 and FS&nbsp;1133.<ref name=Port/>

[[File:USS Upshur (DD-144).jpg|thumb|The {{sclass|Wickes|destroyer}} {{USS|Upshur|DD-144|6}} was one of 23 warships that escorted Convoy UGS&nbsp;14.]]
''Fort Stikine'' departed from Middlesbrough on 20 June to join Convoy FN&nbsp;1051,<ref name=Port/> which had departed from [[Southend-on-Sea|Southend]], [[Essex]] the previous day and arrived at Methil on 21 June.<ref name=FN1051>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/fn/index.html?fn.php?convoy=1051!~fnmain |title=Convoy FN.1051 = Convoy FN.51 / Phase 11 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> She then joined Convoy EN&nbsp;246 which sailed the next day and arrived at Loch Ewe on 24 June.<ref name=Port/> ''Fort Stikine'' joined Convoy ON&nbsp;190, which had departed from Liverpool on 24 June. The convoy consisted of 85 merchant ships escorted by 23 warships over the duration of the convoy, which arrived at New York on 9 July.<ref name=ON246>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/on/index.html?onz.php?convoy=190!~onzmain |title=Convoy ON.246 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> ''Fort Stikine'' sailed on to [[Baltimore, Maryland]], arriving the next day. She departed from Baltimore on 3 August for the [[Hampton Roads]], off the coast of [[Virginia]].<ref name=Port/> ''Fort Stikine'' sailed on 7 August with Convoy UGS&nbsp;14. The convoy consisted of 106 merchant ships escorted by 31 warships over the duration of the convoy. Two merchant ships were lost to enemy action. The convoy arrived at [[Alexandria]], [[Kingdom of Egypt|Egypt]] on 2 September.<ref name=UGS14>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/ugs/index.html?ugs.php?convoy=14!~ugsmain |title=Convoy UGS.14 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> ''Fort Stikine'' departed from Alexandria on 22 September and sailed via [[Port Said]] and [[Suez]] to [[Aden]], where she arrived on 30 September.<ref name=Port/>

[[File:HMS Stork 1943 IWM FL 22540.jpg|thumb|The {{sclass|Bittern|sloop}} {{HMS|Stork|L81|6}} was one of the sixteen warships that escorted Convoy GUS&nbsp;25.]]
On 10 October, ''Fort Stikine'' departed from Aden with Convoy AKD&nbsp;3. The unescorted convoy, consisting eighteen merchant vessels, arrived at [[Durban]], [[Union of South Africa|South Africa]] on 29 October.<ref name=AKD3>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/misc/index.html?yy.php?convoy=AKD.3!~miscmain |title=Convoy AKD.3 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> She left the convoy at [[Beira, Mozambique]], arriving on 26 October. ''Fort Stikine'' sailed on 11 November and joined Convoy DKA&nbsp;6.<ref name=Port/> The unescorted convoy, consisting 20 merchant ships in total, had departed from Durban five days earlier and arrived at Aden on 28 November,<ref name=DKA6>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/misc/index.html?yy.php?convoy=DKA.6!~miscmain |title=Convoy DKA.6 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> but ''Fort Stikine'' had put in to [[Dar es Salaam]], [[Tanganyika Territory|Tanganyika]], where she arrived on 17 November. She sailed on 20 November for [[Mombasa]], [[British Kenya|Kenya]], arriving the next day. She sailed a week later for Aden, from where she departed on 9 December for Suez and Port Said, arriving at the latter port on 19 December.<ref name=Port/> ''Fort Stikine'' was a member of Convoy GUS&nbsp;25, which departed from Port Said on 16 December. The convoy, consisting 106 merchant ships escorted by sixteen warships over its duration, arrived at the Hampton Roads on 17 January 1944. One merchant vessel was lost to enemy action.<ref name=GUS25>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/gus/index.html?gus.php?convoy=25!~gusmain |title=Convoy GUS.25 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> ''Fort Stikine'' left the convoy at Gibraltar, where she arrived on 28 December 1943.<ref name=Port/>

Laden with [[copper]], [[sisal]] and general cargo, ''Fort Stikine'' departed from Gibraltar on 11 January 1944 as a member of Convoy MKS&nbsp;36G. The convoy, of twenty merchant ships and five escorting warships, made a rendezvous at sea with Convoy SL&nbsp;145 the next day.<ref name=MKS36G>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/mks/index.html?mks.php?convoy=36G!~mksmain |title=Convoy MKS.36G |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> The combined convoy arrived at Liverpool on 24 January.<ref name=Port/>

''Fort Stikine'' loaded at [[Birkenhead]], [[Cheshire]].<ref name=EB>{{cite web |url=http://www.merchantnavyofficers.com/bomEx.html |title=Explosion in Bombay |publisher=Merchant Navy Officers |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> Her cargo was described as general cargo;<ref name=OS69KM/> it consisted {{convert|1396|LT|t}} of [[flare|flares and signal rockets]], [[incendiary bomb]]s, [[naval mine|mines]], [[shell (projectile)|shells]] and [[torpedo]]es. These were bound for [[Bombay]], [[British Raj|India]]. A container with 31 crates each containing four [[gold]] bars was loaded in <U+2116> 2 hold. Each gold bar weighed {{convert|28|lb|kg|2}}. She was also carrying twelve [[Supermarine Spitfire]] aircraft, some [[military glider|gliders]] and a further quantity of explosives that were destined to be offloaded at [[Karachi]], India.<ref name=EB/>

[[File:HMS Jonquil (K68) IWM FL 22394.jpg|thumb|The {{sclass|Flower|corvette}} {{HMS|Jonquil|K68|6}} was one of the four escorts of Convoy OS&nbsp;69KM.]]
''Fort Stikine'' joined Convoy OS&nbsp;69KM,<ref name=Port/> which departed from Liverpool on 23 February 1944. The convoy, consisting of 49 merchant ships escorted by twelve warships, split at sea on 5 March.<ref name=OS69KM>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/os/index.html?os.php?convoy=69KM!~osmain |title=Convoy OS.69/KMS.43 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> The two convoys thus formed were OS&nbsp;69, which arrived at Freetown on 15 March;<ref name=OS69>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/os/index.html?os.php?convoy=69KM!~osmain |title=Convoy OS.69 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> and Convoy KMS&nbsp;43G, which arrived at Gibraltar on 6 March.<ref name=Port/> During the voyage to Gibraltar, a [[stowaway]] was discovered. He was put to work under the charge of the ship's Chief Engineer.<ref name=EB/>

[[File:Focke Wulf Fw200.jpg|thumb|Convoy KMS&nbsp;43 successfully evaded an attack by [[Focke-Wulf Fw 200 Condor]] aircraft.]]
''Fort Stikine'' continued her voyage as part of Convoy KMS&nbsp;43, which departed from Gibraltar that day. The convoy, consisting 81 merchant ships and 4 escorting warships, arrived at Port Said on 16 March,<ref name=KM43>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/kms/index.html?kms.php?convoy=43!~kmsmain |title=Convoy KM.43 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> having evaded an attack by four [[Focke-Wulf Fw 200 Condor]] aircraft.<ref name=EB/> She sailed on to Suez, from where she departed the next day for Aden.<ref name=Port/> The stowaway was offloaded at Port Tawfiq, Suez.<ref name=EB/> Having reached Aden on 23 March, she sailed the same day for Karachi, arriving on 30 March.<ref name=Port/>

To replace the cargo offloaded at Karachi, 8,700 bales of raw [[cotton]] were loaded, along with various quantities of fish manure, [[resin]], [[rice]], [[iron|scrap iron]], [[sulphur]], and [[timber]]. Added to this were 1,000 barrels of [[lubricant|lubricating oil]]. The ship's captain was concerned about having to take the flammable items but was told that they had to go. A proposal to add 750 drums of [[turpentine]] was refused. The ship's officers also expressed concerns over mixing the cargoes of cotton and the oil and explosives, but were unable to find paperwork that advised against this practice. In 1942, the [[United States Government]] had published a book which advised against the carriage of raw cotton. A common myth at the time was that wet cotton bales could [[spontaneous combustion|spontaneously combust]]. This was not the case, although cotton soaked in oil would readily do so. Before the ship sailed, the crew discovered that the barrels of lubricating oil leaked. Tarpaulins were nailed over the lower hold covers and the firefighting equipment on board was thoroughly tested. Extra fire drills were scheduled during the voyage to Karachi.<ref name=EB/> ''Fort Stikine'' sailed on 9 April to join Convoy PB&nbsp;74,<ref name=Port/> which had departed from [[Bandar Abbas]], Iran on 6 April. The unescorted convoy arrived at Bombay on 12 April.<ref name=PB74>{{cite web |url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/misc/index.html?yy.php?convoy=PB.74!~miscmain |title=Convoy PB.74 |publisher=Convoyweb |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref>

==Loss==
{{main|Bombay Explosion (1944)}}
''Fort Stikine'' arrived at Bombay in the early morning of 12 April. Having taken on a [[maritime pilot|pilot]] shortly before 10:00 she was docked at the Victoria Dock at midday. The practice of flying a red flag to signify dangerous cargo on board had been discontinued in wartime as doing so would identify such vessels in the event of an enemy air raid on a port. Also, the practice on unloading such vessels into [[lighter (barge)|lighters]] offshore had also been discontinued due to the war. At the time, explosives were graded as Category A, B, or C. Category A explosives, such as those carried on board ''Fort Stikine'', were the most dangerous. These were only allowed to be offloaded onto lighters, and not directly to the quayside.<ref name=EB/>

Unloading of ''Fort Stikine'' began with the lubricating oil, followed by the fish manure. An extra gang of [[stevedore]]s were employed on this task, which continued through the night of 13<U+2013>14 April. At midday on 13 April, lighters arrived for the explosives. Minor engine repairs also started at that time, rendering the ship unable to move under her own power. At 12:30, the Chief Officer of {{SS|Fort Crevier||2}} noticed smoke issuing from the ventilators of the <U+2116> 2 hold of ''Fort Stikine''. This was also seen a short time later by a [[Defensively Equipped Merchant Ship|DEMS]] gunner on board {{SS|Iran|1919|2}}. Despite being seen by these (and other) witnesses, everyone assumed that the situation was under control. The alarm was not raised until 13:45. The fire pump in the ship's engine room was started and the firefighting operation began.<ref name=EB/>

With crew members and stevedores abandoning ship, it was realised by the dock authorities that there was a problem on board ''Fort Stikine''. A fire crew was sent on board and an order was given for more [[fire appliance|fire engines]] to be sent for. Due to difficulties in contacting the fire control centre, initially only two engines were sent. Those on board ''Fort Stikine'' were unable to discover the seat of the fire and water was poured blindly into the hold. With the arrival of the two fire appliances, there were now eleven hoses in use. Captain Oberst, of the [[Indian Army Ordnance Corps]] arrived a few minutes later to assess the situation. He was in charge of the explosives only after they had been landed. A meeting was held on board between the ship's officers, Oberst, and Commander Longmore of the [[Royal Indian Navy]], the Chief Salvage Officer in Bombay. It was stated by Oberst that ''Fort Stikine'' had explosives equivalent to 150 [[Blockbuster bomb]]s on board and that the ship should be [[scuttling|scuttled]]. Her captain countered that the boiler room and engine room could be flooded, but he doubted that the ship would sink in that condition. More fire appliances arrived, bringing the total number of hoses in use to 32. by 14:45, ammunition in <U+2116> 2 hold was exploding. Colonel Sadler, the General Manager of the docks at Bombay, was sent for. He arrived at 14:50 and suggested that ''Fort Stikine'' should be removed from the docks, which would have required the use of [[tugboat|tugs]] due to ''Fort Stikine'' being disabled. An argument developed and Colonel Sadler's parting remark was that the ship would probably explode before she could be taken out of port.<ref name=EB/>

[[File:Bombay-Docks-aftermath1.png|thumb|A cloud of smoke over Bombay following the first explosion on board ''Fort Stikine''.]]
Shortly after 15:00, two [[fireboat]]s, the ''Doris'' and ''Panwell'', arrived. A further nine hoses were played on the ship. Neither of the two people who could have taken overall charge of the situation were contactable, and none of those on board ''Fort Stikine'' were willing to take charge. Firefighting continued, but at 15:50 a flame erupted from the hold, reaching higher than the ship's mast. The order was given to abandon ship, with some jumping from the ship onto the quayside, and others into the water. At 16:06, an explosion occurred on board ''Fort Stikine''. The ship was split in two, with her boiler found half a mile (800m) away. The explosion caused a [[tsunami]] within the dock, which deposited one vessel on the quayside. At 16:33, a second explosion occurred. The cargo ship {{SS|Jalapadma|1926|2}} had her stern blown off. It landed about {{convert|200|yd|m}} away. This explosion also wrecked the cargo liner {{SS|Baroda||2}}.<ref name=EB/>

===Investigation===
The accident was investigated by the authorities at Bombay. The report was released on 11 September 1944 and concluded that the fire and subsequent explosion on ''Fort Stikine'' was an accident. Sabotage was ruled out. The death toll was given as 231 service and port personnel killed, with 476 injured. Civilian casualties were in excess of 500 killed, with 2,408 treated in hospital.<ref name=Times120944>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=THE EXPLOSIONS AT BOMBAY |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=12 September 1944 |page_number=3 |issue=49556 |column=E }}</ref>

